ng claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":6,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":16,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Augustin de Minshull I was born in 1090, in Church Minshull, Cheshire, England as the son of Aregrim de Minshull and Mrs Aregrim de Minshull. He married Mrs. Augustin de Mynshull I in 1110, in Church Minshull, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"1090–":"1090–Surnud","1090–Male":"1090–Surnud","1090–Female":"1090–Surnud","1116–Male":"1116–Surnud","1125–Female":"1125–Surnud","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1060–Male":"1060–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1090":"1090","before 1090":"enne 1090","1106":"1106","1116":"1116","1125":"1125","1110":"1110","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1060":"1060","Church Minshull, Cheshire, England":"Church Minshull, Cheshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1090–":"1090–Kuollut","1090–Male":"1090–Kuollut","1090–Fem